4: A histogram of the p-values from the regression in Q3

pvalue <- summary(model)$coefficient[,4]
hist(pvalue)

ks.test(pvalue, "punif") # Null hypothesis is that output distribution is uniform
## 
##  Asymptotic one-sample Kolmogorov-Smirnov test
## 
## data:  pvalue
## D = 0.021705, p-value = 0.7338
## alternative hypothesis: two-sided
print("The histogram look likes a uniform distribution.")
## [1] "The histogram look likes a uniform distribution."

5: How many significant variables do you expect to find knowing how the data was generated? How many significant variables does the regression yeild if alpha = 0.01? What does this tell us?

(table(pvalue<0.01))
## 
## FALSE  TRUE 
##   988    12
  1. I expect that none variable will be significant as the data are purely randomly generated.
  2. However, the result shows that there are 11 p-values are tested as statically significant if alpha = 0.01.
  3. This difference tells us that: when one model has too many variables(e.g., 1000 in this example), alpha percent of total variables would be wrongly tested as statistically significant but these variables actually are not significant and meaningful at all. In the case, we need to be careful when we include too many variables in the model.

6: Use the BH procedure to control the FDR with a q of 0.1. How many true discoveries do you estimate?

q <- 0.1
ranked_p <- sort(pvalue)
k <- seq(1,length(ranked_p),1)
pstar <- q*(k/length(ranked_p))
compare <- ranked_p < pstar
table <- cbind(ranked_p,k,pstar, compare)
#View(table)
table(table[compare])
## < table of extent 0 >
print("None 'true' discovery founded.")
## [1] "None 'true' discovery founded."

9: Why might false discoveries be an issue?

  1. False discoveries will negatively influence the accuracy of the model and its prediction. i.e., if the model wrongly includes insignificant variables, then the price prediction will be biased.
  2. This model has over 50 variables and 22 variables are tested as statistically significant.
  3. Lets say the alpha is 5%, also suppose that half of all the regression coefficients are actually influential and that we find all of them significant. Still, around 2 (=52/2*0.05) tests would be wrongly put as significant. That is, around 10% of significant tests are false discoveries.
  4. Also, for every 10 variables added in the model esp.for dummy variables and an alpha of 0.05, the expected number of false detection will increase by 0.5 accordingly, which is not a good thing. Thus, the false discoveries might be an issue.

10: Use the BH procedure to control the FDR with a q of 0.1. How many true discoveries do you estimate? Plot the cutoff line together with the significant and insignificant p-values.

qauto <- 0.1
pvals <- summary(model2)$coefficient[-1,4]
psorted <- sort(pvals)
prank <- seq(1,length(psorted),1)
pnew <- qauto*(prank/length(psorted))
tag <- psorted <= pnew
table2 <- cbind(prank,pvals,psorted,pnew,tag)
#View(table2)
table(tag)
## tag
## FALSE  TRUE 
##    33    19
print("There are 19 true discoveries.")
## [1] "There are 19 true discoveries."
## extract p-value cutoff for E[fdf] < q
fdr <- function(pvals, q, plotit){
  pvals <- pvals[!is.na(pvals)]
  N <- length(pvals)
  
  k <- rank(pvals, ties.method="min")
  alpha <- max(pvals[ pvals <= (q*k/N) ])
  
  if(plotit){
    sig <- factor(pvals <= alpha)
    o <- order(pvals)
    plot(pvals[o], log="xy", col=c("grey60","red")[sig[o]], pch=20, 
      ylab="p-values", xlab="tests ordered by p-value", main = paste('FDR =',q))
    lines(1:N, q*(1:N) / N)
  }
  
  return(alpha)
}
(fdr(pvals, q, plotit=TRUE)) 

## [1] 0.02956354
print("The cutoff value is 0.02956354.")
## [1] "The cutoff value is 0.02956354."
